= Soil Formation and Properties
== Soil Horizons and Types
- Soil forms from weathered rock, organic matter, and climate effects.
- Soil horizons: O (organic), A (humus), E (leached), B (deposition), C (parent material), R (rock).
#figure(
  image(images.at("4.21").path, width: 50%),
)
- Weathering is strongest in warm, wet climates, producing deep, nutrient-poor soils.
#figure(
  image(images.at("4.22").path, width: 50%),
)
- Podsolization (cool, moist climates) and laterization (tropical climates) reduce soil fertility.
#figure(
  image(images.at("4.23").path, width: 50%),
)
#figure(
  image(images.at("4.24").path, width: 50%),
)

== Soil Chemistry and Fertility
- Clay particles hold nutrients via cation exchange; fertility depends on clay and organic content.
- Acidic soils and heavy rainfall leach nutrients, lowering productivity.

